│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs when the VPlan-native path attempts to widen a call as an    │
│ intrinsic, but the call is not an LLVM intrinsic. Specifically,               │
│ VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe::execute calls isVectorIntrinsicWithOverloadTypeAtArg  │
│ with an Intrinsic::ID that is Intrinsic::not_intrinsic (0), triggering the    │
│ assertion in VectorUtils.cpp that the ID must not be not_intrinsic.           │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows that the VPlan builder created a VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe   │
│ for a non-intrinsic call: "WIDEN-INTRINSIC void callnot_intrinsic()". This    │
│ indicates the call to @use was incorrectly categorized as an intrinsic during │
│ the initial VPlan construction. The stack trace pinpoints the failure at      │
│ VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe::execute, which, for intrinsics, queries overload info │
│ in VectorUtils and asserts the ID is not not_intrinsic.                       │
│                                                                               │
│ The log also shows this path is taken very early (first transformation)       │
│ within the VPlan-native path. Scalar-evolution and legality are fine; the     │
│ failure is due to the VPlan construction incorrectly treating a regular call  │
│ as an intrinsic recipe.                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In VPlanTransforms.cpp, when lowering IR to a plain VPlan (HCFGBuilder path), │
│ CallInsts are unconditionally turned into a VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe using      │
│ getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, &TLI), regardless of whether that function is │
│ actually an intrinsic:                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│   } else if (CallInst *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(Inst)) {                       │
│     NewRecipe = new VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe(                                   │
│         *CI, getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, &TLI),                           │
│         {Ingredient.op_begin(), Ingredient.op_end() - 1}, CI->getType(),      │
│         CI->getDebugLoc());                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ If the call is not an intrinsic, getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall returns          │
│ Intrinsic::not_intrinsic (0). Passing that into VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe leads  │
│ to later calls to VectorUtils asserting. This contradicts                     │
│ VPRecipeBuilder::tryToWidenCall, which correctly guards intrinsic handling    │
│ with ID != not_intrinsic and otherwise chooses a VPWidenCallRecipe or falls   │
│ back.                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the bug is in VPlanTransforms.cpp: it must not emit                │
│ VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe for non-intrinsic calls. It should either emit a       │
│ VPWidenCallRecipe (for regular library calls) or a replicate recipe when      │
│ appropriate. The minimal fix is to guard the intrinsic creation and otherwise │
│ create a VPWidenCallRecipe using the original called function as the variant, │
│ preserving the call semantics in the plain CFG VPlan.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp                       │
│ Lines: 86-91 (inside the else-if handling CallInst)                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Change the unconditional VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe construction to check the     │
│ returned ID and fall back to VPWidenCallRecipe when ID ==                     │
│ Intrinsic::not_intrinsic. Concretely:                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ - Before:                                                                     │
│   NewRecipe = new VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe(                                     │
│       *CI, getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, &TLI),                             │
│       {Ingredient.op_begin(), Ingredient.op_end() - 1}, CI->getType(),        │
│       CI->getDebugLoc());                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ - After:                                                                      │
│   Intrinsic::ID ID = getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, &TLI);                   │
│   if (ID != Intrinsic::not_intrinsic) {                                       │
│     NewRecipe = new VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe(                                   │
│         *CI, ID,                                                              │
│         {Ingredient.op_begin(), Ingredient.op_end() - 1}, CI->getType(),      │
│         CI->getDebugLoc());                                                   │
│   } else {                                                                    │
│     // For non-intrinsic calls, emit a VPWidenCallRecipe using the original   │
│     // called function as the variant; operands include the callee as the     │
│ last                                                                          │
│     // operand.                                                               │
│     Function *CalledFn = cast<Function>(                                      │
│         Ingredient.getOperand(Ingredient.getNumOperands() -                   │
│ 1)->getLiveInIRValue());                                                      │
│     NewRecipe = new VPWidenCallRecipe(CI, CalledFn,                           │
│                                       {Ingredient.op_begin(),                 │
│ Ingredient.op_end()},                                                         │
│                                       CI->getDebugLoc());                     │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures non-intrinsic calls are no longer represented as intrinsic       │
│ recipes, preventing the assertion failure during execution.                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to VPlanTransforms incorrectly creating                      │
│ VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe for a non-intrinsic call, leaving Intrinsic::ID as     │
│ not_intrinsic and triggering a later assertion. Guarding the creation on ID   │
│ != not_intrinsic and falling back to VPWidenCallRecipe for normal calls fixes │
│ the issue. The expected effect is that the reproducer no longer aborts;       │
│ non-intrinsic calls will be modeled as widened calls in the VPlan rather than │
│ intrinsics, and the vectorizer can proceed or choose appropriate handling     │
│ later without violating intrinsic assumptions.                                │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
